WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
Hi, my name is Steph Hazlitt, and I'm here to share with you three reasons why I hope

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:20.160
you will join me at the Big Data with Arrow in R workshop at PositConf this coming September.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:28.040
My first reason, doing data analysis on bigger and bigger data is becoming commonplace for

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:34.160
many data professionals, and I think that it is fair to say that our data is only going

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:36.400
to get bigger.

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:42.040
In the Big Data with Arrow in R workshop, you will learn how to wrangle your very large

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:48.580
data, even when that data is so large it won't fit on the memory of your computer.

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:51.240
This will feel like a superpower.

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:59.520
My second reason, you will learn to wrangle your too-large-for-memory data on your computer

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:05.919
without having to learn a new programming language or even new R syntax.

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:11.919
You'll be introduced to Apache Arrow, which is a toolkit designed for efficient in-memory

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:15.919
data analysis on our large data.

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:20.419
And the Arrow for R package is built with a dplyr backend, so you'll be wrangling this

00:01:20.419 --> 00:01:28.660
large data on your laptop with familiar to you dplyr and base R syntax.

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:34.000
My third reason, along the way while we are learning these things, you will pick up many

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.199
data engineering tips and tricks that will definitely save you time and friction when

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:43.980
you're building out your data workflows using R, and especially when you're building those

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:49.300
data workflows with growing or already very large datasets.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:53.639
And I'm going to throw in a bonus reason for joining me at the Big Data with Arrow

00:01:53.639 --> 00:01:59.379
in R workshop, and that is I'll be co-instructing with Nick Crane.

00:01:59.379 --> 00:02:01.320
This is Nick.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:07.300
Not only is Nick an R educator, Nick is currently one of the core developers and maintainers

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:12.479
of the Arrow for R package, so we will have an expert in the room with us.

00:02:12.479 --> 00:02:18.580
So if you are ready to tackle those two big datasets in your life with Arrow using R,

00:02:18.580 --> 00:02:24.500
please join Nick and I at the PositConf 2023 in Chicago.

